info: This corpus is an automatically annotated version of data from the Parallel Bible Corpus (Mayer & Cysouw 2014) that has been reduced in scope for the purposes of crosslinguistic research. Metadata from the original PBC file is included in this dict for reference, as well as the license information and the automatic POS annotations. The first three characters of the filename corresponds to the ISO 639-3 code for the respective language. The `tagged` key in this dict contains a list of lists, with the first item in each sublist being the verse number (following PBC convention) and the second being a list of tuples in [word, POS] format where `unk` represents unknown tags.

metadata: # english_title: The New Testament in Zapotec de Yaganiza

# copyright_long: Zapotec, Cajonos (zad) Mexico
The Zapotec language(s) are a group of closely related indigenous Mesoamerican languages spoken by the Zapotec people from the southwestern-central highlands of Mexico. The population of the Cajonos is approximately 5,000 in Mexico There are many monolinguals. They live in the region of North Oaxaca, San Pedro Cajonos, San Francisco Cajonos, San Mateo Cajonos, San Miguel Cajonos, San Pablo Yaganiza, Xagacía. Also in United States. Alternate names are Southern Villa Alta Zapotec, Zapoteco de San Pedro Cajonos Dialects Cajonos Zapotec, Yaganiza, Xagacía Zapotec, San Mateo Zapotec. Yaganiza and Xagacía. Dialects are similar. There is a 73% intelligibility with San Pedro Cajonos with Zoogocho [zpq] (most similar other Zapotec). Language classification is Oto-Manguean, Zapotecan, Zapotec A member of macrolanguage Zapotec [zap] (Mexico). Language development includes a Bilingual primary school, Dictionary and Bible portions The Writing system is in the Latin script. Zapotec, Cajonos is a tonal language.
